PiperOrigin-RevId: 358880444
Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358880444
Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

  custom calls that users write still expect to get buffer pointers for these token types.
- To be able to support this, add an optional call target argument mapping attribute to
  LMHLO custom calls. When this attribute is present, it indicates the number of
  arguments and returns that the custom call expects and also indicates which LMHLO
  arg() or output() maps to which arg or result number of the custom call.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

- XLA:HLO -> LMHLO conversion drops all token arguments and return values, however
  custom calls that users write still expect to get buffer pointers for these token types.
- To be able to support this, add an optional call target argument mapping attribute to
  LMHLO custom calls. When this attribute is present, it indicates the number of
  arguments and returns that the custom call expects and also indicates which LMHLO
  arg() or output() maps to which arg or result number of the custom call.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yongtang/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

[{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

[{"sha":"42dba8c3f9a821c64864c49e60fff9b3ba3e86c5","author":{"name":"Rob Cowsill","email":"4ced00c28ea0046018d361ef4a0a1cf292775363@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix spurious error from "docker load"

"docker load" validates parent links by comparing image histories, and the
History struct has a time.Time member "Created". Time.UnmarshalJSON can read
RFC3339 timestamps with offset "+00:00", but t.MarshalJSON writes them with
offset "Z". Equivalent times in these two formats are not equal when compared
with the == operator.

This causes checkValidParent to incorrectly return false when the parent image
history contains times using offset "+00:00". In that case the history copied
to the child image will have been converted into "Z" form when marshaled out.

This patch adds an "Equal" method to History, which compares "Created" times
with t.Equal. This is used instead of reflect.DeepEqual in checkValidParent.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358880444
Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

[{"sha":"42dba8c3f9a821c64864c49e60fff9b3ba3e86c5","author":{"name":"Rob Cowsill","email":"4ced00c28ea0046018d361ef4a0a1cf292775363@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix spurious error from "docker load"

"docker load" validates parent links by comparing image histories, and the
History struct has a time.Time member "Created". Time.UnmarshalJSON can read
RFC3339 timestamps with offset "+00:00", but t.MarshalJSON writes them with
offset "Z". Equivalent times in these two formats are not equal when compared
with the == operator.

This causes checkValidParent to incorrectly return false when the parent image
history contains times using offset "+00:00". In that case the history copied
to the child image will have been converted into "Z" form when marshaled out.

This patch adds an "Equal" method to History, which compares "Created" times
with t.Equal. This is used instead of reflect.DeepEqual in checkValidParent.

[{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Manas1820/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358880444
Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

[{"sha":"8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"internal/moduletest: Experimental module testing helpers

As part of ongoing research into Terraform testing we'd like to use an
experimental feature to validate our current understanding that expressing
tests as part of the Terraform language, as opposed to in some other
language run alongside, is a good and viable way to write practical
module integration tests.

This initial experimental incarnation of that idea is implemented as a
provider, just because that's an easier extension point for research
purposes than a first-class language feature would be. Whether this would
ultimately emerge as a provider similar to this or as custom language
constructs will be a matter for future research, if this first
experiment confirms that tests written in the Terraform language are the
best direction to take.

The previous incarnation of this experiment was an externally-developed
provider apparentlymart/testing, listed on the Terraform Registry. That
helped with showing that there are some useful tests that we can write
in the Terraform language, but integrating such a provider into Terraform
will allow us to make use of it in the also-experimental "terraform test"
command, which will follow in subsequent commits, to see how this might
fit into a development workflow.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c"},{"sha":"7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Experimental "terraform test" command

This is just a prototype to gather some feedback in our ongoing research
on integration testing of Terraform modules. The hope is that by having a
command integrated into Terraform itself it'll be easier for interested
module authors to give it a try, and also easier for us to iterate quickly
based on feedback without having to coordinate across multiple codebases.

Everything about this is subject to change even in future patch releases.
Since it's a CLI command rather than a configuration language feature it's
not using the language experiments mechanism, but generates a warning
similar to the one language experiments generate in order to be clear that
backward compatibility is not guaranteed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e"},{"sha":"8d37a709877db9004f896db92ddc5e95837be378","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"website: Initial docs for the module integration testing experiment

Since this is still at an early phase and likely to change significantly
in future iterations, rather than attempting to guess on a suitable final
location for documenting the testing feature I've instead taken the
unusual approach of adding a new page that is explicitly about the
experiment. My expectation is that once we conclude the experiment we'll
replace this new page with a stub that just explains that there was once
an experiment and then links to whatever final feature unfolded from the
research.

The URL for this page is hard-coded into the warning message in the
"terraform test" command, so as we continue to evolve this feature in
future releases we'll need to update the callout note on the page about
which Terraform CLI version it's currently talking about, so users of
older versions can clearly see when they'd need to upgrade in order to
participate in a later incarnation of the experiment.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/8d37a709877db9004f896db92ddc5e95837be378"}]

[{"sha":"42dba8c3f9a821c64864c49e60fff9b3ba3e86c5","author":{"name":"Rob Cowsill","email":"4ced00c28ea0046018d361ef4a0a1cf292775363@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix spurious error from "docker load"

"docker load" validates parent links by comparing image histories, and the
History struct has a time.Time member "Created". Time.UnmarshalJSON can read
RFC3339 timestamps with offset "+00:00", but t.MarshalJSON writes them with
offset "Z". Equivalent times in these two formats are not equal when compared
with the == operator.

This causes checkValidParent to incorrectly return false when the parent image
history contains times using offset "+00:00". In that case the history copied
to the child image will have been converted into "Z" form when marshaled out.

This patch adds an "Equal" method to History, which compares "Created" times
with t.Equal. This is used instead of reflect.DeepEqual in checkValidParent.

Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kokizzu/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Nicholas282787728/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358880444
Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Cache-Cloud/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

[{"sha":"42dba8c3f9a821c64864c49e60fff9b3ba3e86c5","author":{"name":"Rob Cowsill","email":"4ced00c28ea0046018d361ef4a0a1cf292775363@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix spurious error from "docker load"

"docker load" validates parent links by comparing image histories, and the
History struct has a time.Time member "Created". Time.UnmarshalJSON can read
RFC3339 timestamps with offset "+00:00", but t.MarshalJSON writes them with
offset "Z". Equivalent times in these two formats are not equal when compared
with the == operator.

This causes checkValidParent to incorrectly return false when the parent image
history contains times using offset "+00:00". In that case the history copied
to the child image will have been converted into "Z" form when marshaled out.

This patch adds an "Equal" method to History, which compares "Created" times
with t.Equal. This is used instead of reflect.DeepEqual in checkValidParent.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358880444
Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedisgoood/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358880444
Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358880444
Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Jeffkeen7/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaoxiaopingzi/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

[{"sha":"42dba8c3f9a821c64864c49e60fff9b3ba3e86c5","author":{"name":"Rob Cowsill","email":"4ced00c28ea0046018d361ef4a0a1cf292775363@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix spurious error from "docker load"

"docker load" validates parent links by comparing image histories, and the
History struct has a time.Time member "Created". Time.UnmarshalJSON can read
RFC3339 timestamps with offset "+00:00", but t.MarshalJSON writes them with
offset "Z". Equivalent times in these two formats are not equal when compared
with the == operator.

This causes checkValidParent to incorrectly return false when the parent image
history contains times using offset "+00:00". In that case the history copied
to the child image will have been converted into "Z" form when marshaled out.

This patch adds an "Equal" method to History, which compares "Created" times
with t.Equal. This is used instead of reflect.DeepEqual in checkValidParent.

[{"sha":"1e278329b59cb8f3ee676a9fd0d156d4707e3520","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"internal/moduletest: Experimental module testing helpers

As part of ongoing research into Terraform testing we'd like to use an
experimental feature to validate our current understanding that expressing
tests as part of the Terraform language, as opposed to in some other
language run alongside, is a good and viable way to write practical
module integration tests.

This initial experimental incarnation of that idea is implemented as a
provider, just because that's an easier extension point for research
purposes than a first-class language feature would be. Whether this would
ultimately emerge as a provider similar to this or as custom language
constructs will be a matter for future research, if this first
experiment confirms that tests written in the Terraform language are the
best direction to take.

The previous incarnation of this experiment was an externally-developed
provider apparentlymart/testing, listed on the Terraform Registry. That
helped with showing that there are some useful tests that we can write
in the Terraform language, but integrating such a provider into Terraform
will allow us to make use of it in the also-experimental "terraform test"
command, which will follow in subsequent commits, to see how this might
fit into a development workflow.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/1e278329b59cb8f3ee676a9fd0d156d4707e3520"},{"sha":"bab6fe1f4c6bff1a767cec1157f61773c0435678","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Experimental "terraform test" command

This is just a prototype to gather some feedback in our ongoing research
on integration testing of Terraform modules. The hope is that by having a
command integrated into Terraform itself it'll be easier for interested
module authors to give it a try, and also easier for us to iterate quickly
based on feedback without having to coordinate across multiple codebases.

Everything about this is subject to change even in future patch releases.
Since it's a CLI command rather than a configuration language feature it's
not using the language experiments mechanism, but generates a warning
similar to the one language experiments generate in order to be clear that
backward compatibility is not guaranteed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/bab6fe1f4c6bff1a767cec1157f61773c0435678"},{"sha":"cea28aecd168ec119c23ec57fed9f11690d16f6d","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"website: Initial docs for the module integration testing experiment

Since this is still at an early phase and likely to change significantly
in future iterations, rather than attempting to guess on a suitable final

experiment. My expectation is that once we conclude the experiment we'll
replace this new page with a stub that just explains that there was once
an experiment and then links to whatever final feature unfolded from the
research.

The URL for this page is hard-coded into the warning message in the
"terraform test" command, so as we continue to evolve this feature in
future releases we'll need to update the callout note on the page about
which Terraform CLI version it's currently talking about, so users of
older versions can clearly see when they'd need to upgrade in order to

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/TheAssassinRen/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.

Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358860920
Change-Id: I316f1b43268b268ce50528f7aa307182bce304f6","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/4856f23a49dfe44fb697d5affcf10fb2a2585523"},{"sha":"1e135c54c52a71ae9267011f13fded21cc05fcc3","author":{"name":"David Majnemer","email":"569b955cc968d20f20ebc0fa915938d641b4e895@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small, take two

We approximate it with:
expm1(x) = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

Yet further care must be taken to handle the case when exp(x) would not be all that close to 1, in which case we simply use:
expm1(x) = exp(x)-1

The pseudo-code for this is roughly:
  if x/2 == 0:
    return x
  exp_x = exp(x)
  if |x| > .5:
    return exp_x - 1
  return tanh(x/2)*(exp_x+1)

The actual code sequence emitted preserves vectorization in the case where different lanes observe inputs where the magnitudes are entirely different.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 4.76e-7 or about eight ULPs when
compared against libm.
